        introduction: "The Sarreguemines — Nancy journey crosses Lorraine from end to end, from the German Saarland border to Europe's finest royal square. Sarreguemines, a border town at the confluence of the Saar and Blies, has remarkable industrial and artistic heritage. Its faience manufactories, founded in 1790, produced world-renowned ceramics for over two centuries. The Casino winter garden, entirely decorated with ceramic panels depicting exotic landscapes, is a unique masterpiece of ceramic art. The route crosses the Lorraine coalfield, cradle of mining and steelmaking that powered 20th-century France. Nancy, the destination, is a city of rare elegance. Its Place Stanislas, built 1752-1755 by architect Emmanuel Héré for King Stanislas Leszczyński — Duke of Lorraine and father-in-law of Louis XV — has been UNESCO World Heritage since 1983. Jean Lamour's gilded gates, monumental fountains and the Arc Héré form an urban ensemble of unmatched architectural harmony.",
